tential issue with how Hono handles request body consumption in middleware. When the middleware calls `c.req.json()` to read the body, that stream gets consumed, and the route handler won't be able to read it again. Let me think through whether Hono caches the parsed body internally so this works correctly...\n\nLooking at how Hono actually implements this, it does cache the body after the first read, so calling `c.req.json()` multiple times should work. But to be safe, I could also store the parsed body in the context and have the route handler retrieve it from there instead of re-parsing. the handler gets the same cached promise, so calling `json()` twice should work fine. Now I need to add the clock skew constant to the config and wire the middleware into the router—I'll apply it only to POST routes by either adding it to the sub-router or using a path-based middleware in the main app.\n\nI'm going to go with applying it at the fairness namespace level and checking the method inside the middleware to skip GET requests. My implementation plan is to install tweetnacl, create the auth middleware, update the config, wire it up in the main index, then run typecheck and lint. For the base58 and signature utilities, I should check what's available in the Solana web3 library rather than adding another dependency.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering the approach entirely. Since Node.js 16+ has native Ed25519 support in the crypto module, I can use that to verify signatures without adding tweetnacl or bs58 as dependencies. I'm deciding between adding `tweetnacl` and `bs58` as explicit dependencies versus relying on hoisting, and I need to verify ESM compatibility since the project uses ES modules—`tweetnacl` only exports CommonJS but Node.js can import it in ESM, while `bs58` v5+ has proper ESM support. ESM-native. v4 is CJS.\n\nLet me check what versions are available and choose appropriately. With `pnpm add tweetnacl bs58`:\n- `tweetnacl` latest is 1.0.3 (CJS, but importable from ESM)\n- `bs58` latest is probably v6 which is ESM\n\nActually, `bs58` v5+ depends on `base-x` which is ESM. Let me check...\n\n`bs58` v5.0.0+ is pure ESM. So `pnpm add bs58` should give us v5 or v6. That should work fine with `\"type\": \"module\"`.\n\nFor `tweetnacl`, CJS default export import works fine in Node.js ESM: `import nacl from 'tweetnacl'`\n\nOK let me proceed with the implementation.\n\n`tweetnacl` includes TypeScript declarations natively, so the types should resolve without needing `@types/tweetnacl`. Now I'll install both packages to the backend workspace, then create the auth middleware, update the config and main entry point, and verify everything works.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6046,"cache_read_input_tokens":40624,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6046},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"612240eb-bf1a-44cf-9ae4-1551e7c0525e","uuid":"d3e7074b-cebc-47c6-8f31-979438a36816"}
